tool.name: CalculateTreeHeights

param.name: inputCanopies
param.dialogReference: Input your circular tree canopy or crown polygons. The tool will convert the polygons to point features with tree diameter and height information. These points can then be loaded directly into a 3D Cities Information Model (3DCIM) geodatabase.

param.name: idField
param.dialogReference: Select the Unique ID field within the tree feature class, such as TreeFID.

param.name: inputHeight
param.dialogReference: Select a minimum tree height value. Trees with heights smaller than this value will be removed from the output. (Default is 5 units.)

param.name: inputNDSM
param.dialogReference:
The input normalized Digital Surface Model (nDSM) raster. The nDSM is calculated by subtracting the bare-earth terrain model from the surface model (DSM - DTM = nDSM), and represents a continous "height above ground" surface. These surfaces are easily calculated using classified LiDAR data.

The nDSM raster is used to calculate the maximum height value within each tree polygon, using zonal statistics.

param.name: inputGround
param.dialogReference: The input bare-earth Digital Terrain Model (DTM) raster. The elevation values contained within this raster will be used to vertically align the trees with the ground surface.

param.name: appendValue
param.displayname: Append trees to existing feature class
param.dialogReference: Select option to append trees to an existing feature class, such as the Tree point feature in the 3D Cities Information Model (3DCIM) geodatabase. Unselect to write the output points to a new feature class.

param.name: appendTrees
param.dialogReference: Select the location of the existing tree feature class for which the new trees should be appended, for example to the Tree feature in the 3DCIM geodatabase.

param.name: outputTrees
param.dialogReference: Select the output location of the new tree point feature class.

tool.summary:
Calculates tree height values for input tree canopy polygons. Two raster inputs are needed: a bare-earth Digital Terrain Model (DTM) is used to determine the tree base elevation (the intersection with the ground surface), and a normalized Digital Surface Model (nDSM) is used to determine maximum tree height.

Once base elevation, height and canopy diameter values are available, accurate 3D tree models can easily be generated:
